<TEXT>
president bush will spare the social security 
administration more staff cuts next year amid complaints the agency 
is already understaffed and unable to provide high quality service 
according to government sources 
john sturdivant president of the american federation of 
government employees which represents agency workers said the 
decision to avoid more cutbacks is a signal that perhaps the 
administration has realized the severity of the problem 
we do not have the necessary people that we need to do the 
type of job we want to do sturdivant said this just keeps the 
problem from getting worse it doesnt solve the problem 
the office of management and budget had proposed that social 
securitys staff be cut from 63000 in the current fiscal year to 
58800 in fiscal 1991 but withdrew the plan at the urging of 
health and human services secretary louis sullivan a department 
source said friday 
sullivan and bush met thursday to discuss the hhs budget for 
next year and the president agreed not to seek staff cuts at 
social security said the hhs source and another government 
official who both spoke on condition of anonymity 
bush presents his proposed 1991 spending plan to congress on 
jan 22 
the social security administrations workforce has been slashed 
by 20 percent in the last six years as part of an effort to 
modernize and streamline operations but employees have complained 
they are overworked and unable to properly serve the public 
the decision to avoid further staff cuts was welcomed by sen 
david pryor dark the chairman of senate special committee on 
aging who said it showed a refreshing change of heart after 
reductions in the reagan years 
ssa services provide a view for millions of american of their 
government in action when service deteriorates as it has in the 
reagan years we hear about it pryor said he credited bush 
sullivan and new social security commissioner gwendolyn king for 
opposing further cuts 
eileen sweeney of the national senior citizens law center also 
welcomed news that further cutbacks would be averted but she 
warned that current staffing levels are inadequate 
at 63000 they do not have the staff to run the program 
sweeney said they have staff that are totally overworked 
