<TEXT>
a chinese couple hijacked an air china jumbo jet 
bound for new york with 223 people on board saturday and the 
aircraft was forced to land in western japan authorities said the 
hijackers a man and woman were arrested 
the passengers and crew were reported safe 
the boeing 747 left beijing on saturday morning and made a stop 
in shanghai then abruptly diverted from its course a japanese 
foreign ministery official said 
the couple traveling with a child demanded to be flown to 
taiwan but taiwan refused permission for the aircraft to land 
japanese officials said 
south korea also refused permission for the aircraft to land 
and it flew on to japan south korean officials said 
the aircraft finally landed at fukuoka 560 miles southwest of 
tokyo on japans westernmost main island of kyushu at 252 pm 
1252 am after the pilot said he only had 40 minutes of fuel 
left japanese officials said 
they said the crew overpowered the woman hijacker on the plane 
after the male hijacker jumped to the tarmac below 
the man who was injured and taken to a hospital told japanese 
officials he was one of the hijackers and gave his age as 36 a 
transport ministry official said 
japan broadcasting corp showed a man lying facedown on the 
tarmac and being rushed into a local hospital the network said the 
man gave his name as zhang haixin and that the other two hijackers 
were his wife and child 
the network quoted zhang as saying he belonged to a group called 
the china working nine 
the motive for the hijacking was not immediately clear 
in beijing an official with the civil aviation administration 
of china said the couple was chinese and that the passengers on the 
plane were safe the official said the plane would return to 
beijing and that the flight would set out again for new york on 
sunday 
the official who refused to give his name said he was not sure 
what weapon if any the hijackers had he said chinese and 
japanese officials were discussing their fate 
the airport was closed to all traffic and all flights heading 
toward fukuoka were being diverted elsewhere the public network 
said 
a japanese foreign ministry official said there were 223 people 
on the plane when it was hijacked 
the flight had been scheduled to leave beijing at 10 am 9 
pm est and stop at shanghai before going on to new york 
chinese sources said it was hijacked after the shanghai stop 
japan broadcasting said the aircraft was hijacked before landing in 
shanghai 
japan broadcasting said the hijackers first demanded to fly to 
taiwan seat of the nationalist chinese government but were 
refused permission by taiwan authorities 
china air flight 981 then tried to land in south korea but was 
rejected by south korean authorities said a foreign ministry 
official who by custom would not be identified by name 
taiwan and south korea have no diplomatic relations with china 
the aircraft entered south korean airspace over the southernmost 
island of cheju before turning toward japan a south korean defense 
ministry official said 
in 1983 six chinese hijacked a plane to south korea they were 
imprisoned for less than a year and resettled in taiwan where they 
received heroes welcomes 
two men hijacked another domestic flight to taiwan in may 1988 
a hijacking attempt in april failed when the pilot pretended to 
comply with the hijackers demand to go to taiwan but instead 
landed at the mainland city of fuzhou the hijacker committed 
suicide by detonating explosives strapped to his back 
</TEXT>
