<TEXT>
nasa hopes the prechristmas launch 
of space shuttle columbia on a satellite rescue mission will take 
place thursday 
theres still a lot of work to do between now and then but we 
are reasonably confident of launch on the 21st robert l 
crippen director of the space shuttle program said friday in 
announcing the change 
the oneday postponement followed an announcement on wednesday 
of a twoday postponement if the shuttle is not launched by dec 
23 liftoff would be delayed until at least dec 27 to free workers 
for the christmas holiday 
the delays have been prompted mainly by unfinished work on 
launch pad 39a which hasnt been used for a shuttle launch in 
nearly four years the complex recently completed a twoyear 50 
million refurbishment and it has taken technicians longer than 
expected to validate fuel lines and other systems 
some tiny fuel leaks and other minor problems have turned up 
slowing work 
during 10 days in space columbias five astronauts are to 
release a communications satellite for the navy and then track down 
and retrieve a large science payload before it falls to earth the 
payload has been orbiting for six years and is scheduled to reenter 
the atmosphere in march 
astronaut dan brandenstein is the crew commander the others are 
pilot jim wetherbee and mission specialists bonnie dunbar marsha 
ivins and david low 
