<TEXT>
ninetynine years after his death 
followers of the sioux leader sitting bull paid tribute to his 
spirit with a ceremony in the numbing cold and began a 15day 
spiritual pilgrimage over the frozen plains 
about 20 people gathered friday at a granite marker on the 
standing rock indian reservation near where the chief was buried 
dec 15 1890 the day he died in a shootout with indian police 
with temperatures of 22 below zero the group shared a peace 
pipe and blessings with smoke and ashes from a bowl of cedar chips 
and sweet grass they talked of sitting bulls legacy 
sitting bull fought the us government who sent their best 
army to capture us it never happened said isaac dog eagle a 
descendant of the chief who blessed the site and prayed to the 
grandfathers for protection 
at the 1876 battle of little bighorn the sioux helped defeat 
the 7th cavalry troops led by george armstrong custer killing 
custer and all his soldiers 
before his death sitting bull had united indians in the late 
1800s in their fight against being placed on reservations 
after the ceremony 10 fort yates runners formed a relay team to 
mclaughlin sd about 25 miles south of fort yates their journey 
was to be continued by four men and a woman on horseback from 
sitting bulls old campsite near mclaughlin in a 15day pilgrimage 
to wounded knee sd 
it was at wounded knee on the pine ridge indian reservation 
where sitting bulls followers were killed in a battle with 
custers old cavalry command on dec 29 1890 
the five riders from north dakota were to be met by 13 others in 
south dakota commemorating the journey of sitting bulls 
followers mark white bull 40 of fort yates a member of the 
group said they were riding for spiritual rebirth 
were going to ride for the people suffer for the people so 
that our people may live he said 
we have something to offer the whole world we have this to 
share with the society to go back to basic values 
it was the third year the relay had taken place 
sitting bulls original grave was excavated in the 1960s when 
the us army corps of engineers made a parking area for the 
historic site white bull said the whereabouts of the chiefs 
remains have been debated for years after reports that a south 
dakota group tried to remove them in the 1950s 
the us postal service which cosponsored fridays event 
issued a sitting bull commemorative stamp earlier this year 
after the ceremony at the marker dog eagle told fort yates 
students in the warmth of a standing rock community college 
auditorium that they should be proud of their heritage 
he said drugs alcohol and dependence on nonindian society have 
weakened the indian nations spirit and independence 
the only way we survive is if we go back to being a real 
indian he said 
</TEXT>
