<TEXT>
gen augusto pinochet promised support to 
his newly elected civilian successor but said that the military 
would keep watch over the system he set up during his 16 years of 
iron rule 
pinochets nationwide address showed that the voters defeat of 
his governments policies in balloting thursday would not mean that 
the rightwing army commander would easily turn over total power to 
presidentelect patricio aylwin 
pinochet said we offer all our collaboration not only out of 
respect for those who triumphed in yesterdays elections but also 
out of loyalty to the countrys higher interests which have always 
guided my actions 
he added that the armed forces would rule until the last day 
of their mandate and then would assume a watchdog role to 
guarantee the institutional order of the republic 
a triumphant aylwin told hundreds of thousands of supporters 
friday night that he would insist on the obedience of pinochet and 
the armed forces once he takes office in march 
we want to see the armed forces dedicated to their 
professional duties disciplined obedient recovering the respect 
of all their countrymen aylwin said 
the election was intended to bring back democracy to the last 
south american country still ruled by the military 
pinochet who seized power in a bloody 1973 coup that toppled 
elected president salvador allende was forced to call the election 
after losing a referendum in october 1988 chileans in that vote 
rejected a military proposal that he remain as president until 1997 
in washington the state department congratulated the people and 
the government of chile for the free and honest elections 
the high voter turnout and the orderly and peaceful way in 
which the elections were carried out testify to the strong desire 
of the chilean people to freely elect their political leadership 
the department said in a statement 
late friday there were sporadic clashes with police who 
dispersed small groups of rockthrowing youths with tear gas and 
water cannons police reported at least seven officers hurt and 
dozens of demonstrators detained in the skirmishes downtown which 
lasted well into the night witnesses saw several injured civilians 
taken off in ambulances 
aylwin led the ticket of a 17party centerleft coalition that 
has fought for an end to pinochets authoritarian rule pinochet 
however has vowed to stay on as army commander 
a special constitutional clause bars any new govermment from 
ousting pinochet from the army command for eight years 
aylwin has maintained that the military should limit itself to 
national defense and security matters 
in a news conference the presidentelect declared his 
government will not be a puppet democracy 
he also said he plans to meet with the armed forces before his 
inauguration 
one of the most delicate issues in future militarycivilian 
relations is expected to be an investigation of human rights abuses 
during military rule 
we dont have a wish of revenge but of truth and justice 
aylwin said friday he also said anyone who committed abuses may be 
brought to justice including pinochet 
the 74yearold general says he will not accept human rights 
trials of servicemen and has warned if one of my men is 
touched the state of law will be broken 
aylwin 71 a christian democrat and former senate leader won 
552 percent of the vote progovernment candidate hernan buchi 
finished with 294 percent and a populist businessman francisco 
errazuriz garnered the remaining 154 percent 
voters also picked members of the twochamber congress which 
will reopen for the first time since the 1973 coup 
according to results aylwin will have a 7248 majority in the 
120seat house of deputies and although his coalition won 22 of 
the 38 elected senate seats his government will not have a 
majority the administration is constitutionally empowered to 
appoint up to 10 more senators 
