solidarity leader lech walesa has endorsed 
a tough economic reform package that the government acknowledges 
will cause unemployment and cut incomes 
the solidarity trade union chairmans approval came two days 
before prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki and his cabinet submit the 
plan sunday to parliament 
walesa received a threemember government delegation at his 
gdansk office on friday and said later he supported the 
presented proposals according to a statement released by an aide 
the statement said walesa also expressed the need for 
immediate and radical changes in ownership relations a 
reference to the more than 90 percent of polands nonfarm economy 
controlled by the state 
aleksander hall a cabinet minister in charge of contacts with 
political parties and top officials of the finance and labor 
ministries journeyed to gdansk to present the governments 
socioeconomic program to walesa 
walesa who put together the parliamentary coalition that 
allowed solidarity to take contol of the government from the 
communists in august rejected any office for himself but retains 
close supervision of the government and its programs 
on tuesday walesa caused a sensation in poland when he said the 
need for reform was so urgent that lawmakers should not review the 
package at all but simply give mazowiecki and his government 
special powers to carry out whatever reforms are necessary 
a poll in the solidarity newspaper gazeta wyborcza on friday 
said 50 percent of respondents favored walesas proposal while 16 
percent were definitely against the rest were uncertain 
however the government responded that it wants parliament to 
approve the program because it will require such extensive public 
sacrifices 
the aims of the program are to restructure the polish economy to 
encourage private enterprise and competition choke off rampant 
inflation that reached an estimated 900 percent in 1989 and open 
the economy to foreign trade 
mazowieckis cabinet met through the week to put finishing 
touches on the program which includes tax increases and sharp 
spending cuts to bring the state budget into balance 
government subsidies to enterprises are being cut credit is 
being tightened and coal and energy prices are going up to reflect 
world price levels the changes are expected to squeeze inefficient 
enterprises and force them into bankruptcies 
real incomes are expected to drop 20 percent industrial 
production by 5 percent and the gross national product by 2 to 3 
percent 
many workers are expected to become unemployed at least 
temporarily and the government is creating its first program of 
jobless compensation and retraining it also plans financial aid 
for children and pensioners 
a major aspect of the reform is making the polish currency fully 
convertible inside poland against hard currencies 
the package has been prepared in consultation with the 
international monetary fund which is poised to sign a letter of 
intent next week on an economic adjustment agreement with poland 
including standby loans of 700 million 
the loans are conditioned on poland carrying out its reforms 
once the imf has certified the polish program as meeting the imfs 
tough standards the world bank and western governments are to 
weigh in with other loans worth up to 35 billion 
