<TEXT>
a team of experts from the united states 
britain and south korea joined saturday in urging a drive to reduce 
the numbers of europes 18 million unemployed 
europes longterm unemployed represent its greatest untapped 
resorde they said 
the group consists of economists olivier blanchard rudiger 
dornbusch and paul krugman of the massachusetts institute of 
technology mervyn king and richard layard of the london school of 
economics lawrence h summers of harvard university and yung chul 
park of korea university in seoul 
their report world imbalances was sponsored by world 
institute for development economics research set up in helsinki 
finland as part of the united nations university 
they suggested use of a swedish model to fight unemployment 
intensive placement conseling and retraining services for people 
who lose their jobs unemployment benefits that run out in 14 
months six months of public employment if no job has been found 
and a 50 percent wage subsidy lasting six months for employers who 
hire people who have been out of work for six months 
unemployment in sweden has never been over 35 percent and now 
stands under 15 percent the authors said 
for the united states they recommended an emphasis on increased 
savings low us savings and the accompanying high federal budget 
deficit create a worldwide shortage of capital threaten the world 
trading system and are a likely source of instability in the world 
economy they said 
in addition to reducing the federal budget deficit they 
suggested 
removing social security and its surpluses from the federal 
budget so that the apparent budget deficit is greater and public 
pressure increases to lower it 
restoring the individual retirement account and 
instituting tax incentives for savings such as a deduction 
for employees who as part of their wages will accept stock that 
cannot be sold for five years or a deduction for investment in 
special treasury notes that could not hesold 
they have a radical proposal for third world debt now close to 
13 trillion they would allow interest payments to be made in the 
currency of the debtor countries rather than in hard currencies 
like dollars or yen which are now required 
they said the effect would be to 
stop transfers of funds from debtor countries to creditors 
now running over 50 billion a year 
reduce the uncertainty of exchange rates thus encouraging the 
return of billions of dollars sent abroad for safekeeping by people 
in debtor countries and 
free the foreign currency held by debtor countries for 
purchases of goods in the creditor countries 
in the pacific they warned that a cut in the us budget could 
bring recession to east asia they recommended coordinating the 
policies of the united states and east asian countries on how 
production should be distributed among them 
to prevent the world trading system from breaking into regional 
blocs centered on the united states japan and the european 
economic community they urged 
quick reduction of the us trade deficit and reduction of 
surpluses in japan west germany and the industrializing countries 
of east asia 
easing of what they called the intransigence of the europeans 
on trade in farm products and 
further increases in imports into japan 
</TEXT>
