<TEXT>
enrollment of new students in college and 
university nursing programs rose for the first time in five years 
but this years increase is too little to overcome an acute nursing 
shortage according to a survey released sunday 
the american association of colleges of nursing said enrollment 
of firsttime nursing students in universities and fouryear 
colleges rose by 58 percent in the current 19891990 academic 
year about 60522 new nursing students are pursuing the 
baccalaureate degree both full and parttime this year compared 
with 57154 in the 19881989 academic year an advance copy of the 
survey showed 
combined baccalaureate enrollment including firsttime students 
and registered nurses returning for bachelor degrees is 89546 in 
the current academic year compared with 87700 a year ago an 
increase of 21 percent 
student enrollment may be in the early stages of an upturn 
said association director geraldine bednash but she added the 
road to reversing the nations acute nursing shortage remains a 
long one 
baccalaureate enrollment fell an alarming 319 percent from 
1984 to 1988 but ms bednash said enrollment increases this year 
reduced that fiveyear slide to 177 percent 
overall shortages in student enrollment and in the nursing 
work force will likely continue for several years ms bednash 
said 
in 1988 total graduations of firsttime nurses with 
baccalaureate degrees were 162 percent lower than the year before 
in 1989 graduations of firsttime students about 16003 were 
still 113 percent below 1988 figures 
officials said the survey is based on data received in fall 1989 
from 538 of the nations 623 nursing schools with fouryear 
bachelors degree and graduate degree programs the association 
with more than 400 member institutions nationwide said the report 
represents 124927 fulltime and parttime students in both member 
and nonmember institutions in 50 states the district of columbia 
and us territories 
this is the second consecutive year in which enrollment 
figures have shown some improvement said ms bednash she 
explained that nursing schools in the 198889 academic year had 79 
percent fewer baccalaureate students enrolled than the year before 
but the decline was greatly less than the 145 percent drop seen 
from 198687 
most registered nurses pursue continued education parttime but 
the survey indicated a dramatic 447 percent increase in rns 
those with hospital diplomas or twoyear associate degrees who 
returned to school fulltime during the last five years to earn the 
baccalaureate degree in 1985 there were 4151 rns who returned 
compared with 6010 in 1989 
the data reflect the growing numbers of nurses who are 
furthering their education fulltime to keep pace with the 
increasing complexities and treatment and technological advances in 
todays health care system said the survey 
ms bednash said the signs of change are promising including 
expanded interest in nursing as a rewarding and secure career as 
seen in increased student applications to schools of nursing 
for the current academic year qualified applicants totaled 
16962 compared with 14813 in 198889 an increase of 145 
percent the numbers of students accepted by schools of nursing 
this year at 14717 increased by 144 percent over last years 
total of 12861 
