<TEXT>
its after school on a brilliant wintry day 
but there are no children romping in the snow at the woodside 
apartments where 5yearold melissa lee brannen disappeared from a 
christmas party two weeks ago 
at the school bus stop where perhaps one mother might have 
stood with a dozen children last month now three or four mothers 
wait says resident sally marquis whose 2yearold son daniel 
played with melissa for hours at the apartment complex party from 
which the little girl vanished 
those who arent there you can see them lined up at the 
bottom of the stairs keeping an eye on their youngsters from a 
distance without embarrassing those who think theyre grown up 
enough to wait alone she said 
the middleclass neighborhood around the modern woodside complex 
is tense scared resident susan kunze said 
usually you see kids out all the time at all hours but 
lately its rare that you see a kid out alone without a parent or 
at least a friend she said 
the kunze children diane 9 and joseph 10 know their 
quiet shy little friend melissa has disappeared they also had 
been taught at school and at home long before melissa vanished to 
be wary of strangers and to scream and run if someone tried to grab 
them id scream and kick him in the shins declared joseph 
but when a reporter theyd never met knocked on their apartment 
door the two flung it open with a cheerful hi they left it 
wide open as they raced to get their mother 
being wary of strangers is a lesson that takes time to seep in 
when 10yearold rosie gordon another fairfax county resident 
was abducted and killed last july everyone was shocked that it 
could happen says tammy brannen melissas 27yearold mother 
but people at the woodside apartments adjacent to the towering 
trees of fort belvoir didnt take any special precautions i 
dont think we ever associated it with happening to us she said 
ms brannen who was divorced 2 years ago and moved to her 
apartment in august 1987 seems numb 
it still doesnt really seem real she whispered during an 
interview last week at times it seems like shes over at my 
parents or at school and shes going to walk in the door at any 
minute 
fairfax county police officer michael proffitt said we like 
to think that since it doesnt happen that often that were 
somewhat immune from it but then were shocked back to reality 
that no one is immune from something like this 
the whole region is alert he says reflected by the hundreds of 
phone calls from concerned citizens unfortunately very few 
represent solid leads 
proffitt said melissas case has generated far more rumors than 
any other case in the county 
one false rumor broadcast by some radio and television stations 
was that melissas body had been found in a trash bin 
ms brannen was angered by that report and by reports that an 
apartment complex maintenance man had failed liedetector tests and 
had refused to help police although his wife said he was home late 
dec 3 immediately washed his clothes and cut out parts of his 
