<TEXT>
the drive across the bridge past 
impassive east german border guards was both without precedent in 
american history and a bold but risky venture 
the quiet motorcade to potsdam carried secretary of state james 
a baker iii where no secretary of state had gone before and 
committed the bush administration to a rescue operation for east 
germany as winter approaches 
in his 65minute meeting with hans modrow the reformist prime 
minister and a second session in a 19th century church with 
lutheran ministers who helped bring down the old discredited 
rulers baker heard a tale of a tenuous regime struggling to make 
it to multiparty elections in may and fearful of a violent 
revolution from the streets 
baker the highestlevel us official ever to venture into east 
germany has plunged a oncecautious bush administration into the 
maelstrom of german politics the reunification debate and a 
uniquely dangerous display of what he calls people power 
tuesdays foray after breakfast with west german chancellor 
helmut kohl and a symbolic visit to the disintegrating berlin wall 
topped a busy fiveday trip to europe in which baker also advanced 
a new architecture for the north atlantic treaty organization 
and strengthened us ties to the 12nation european community 
baker neared the end of his trip saturday when he joined 
president bush on the caribbean island of st martin where bush 
was discussing eastwest relations with french president francois 
mitterrand 
the accelerating sweep of economic and political change in 
eastern and central europe calls for policy adjustments in the 
west especially from the united states from a cold war posture of 
confrontation 
the soviets are adjusting too on tuesday foreign minister 
eduard a shevardnadze will call on nato secretarygeneral manfred 
woerner at his brussels headquarters not for negotiations the 
former west german defense minister said 
when poland and hungary first broke away from orthodox 
communism the bush administration responded with what leading 
congressional democrats and many analysts considered to be undue 
caution even timidity 
congress forced increases in aid programs and pushed the white 
house to respond to soviet president mikhail s gorbachevs bold 
arms control programs and need for western technology and economic 
advice 
one of the decisions taken while baker attended a twoday 
meeting of the north atlantic council in brussels was a call for a 
logical system of separating sensitive technology from other 
material that can safely be exported to the east 
we think its still important to protect strategic technology 
but we should rationalize the process to the extent that things 
that are available to some extent off the shelf are not locked up 
in a bureaucratic process particularly at this time of 
significant reform baker said friday at a news conference in 
brussels 
this time around as czechoslovakia bulgaria and especially 
east germany shed hardline leaders and marxist economics the bush 
administration is out front with the promise of the same kind of 
aid given poland and hungary if they keep it up 
there may even be a special food grant to assist the modrow 
