<TEXT>
solidarity leader lech walesa led about 
1000 people saturday in marking the anniversary of the killing of 
scores of baltic coast workers by security forces during 
prechristmas food riots in december 1970 
the annual observance at the towering monument to slain shipyard 
workers just outside the famed lenin shipyard has in the past been 
an occasion for conflict betwen demonstrators and police 
but with solidarity now legal and leading polands government 
walesa used the occasion to tell the crowd including union 
delegations from around poland that the slain workers of 1970 and 
of the december 1981 martiallaw crackdown did not die in vain 
a similar message was sent to the gathering by prime minister 
tadeusz mazowiecki himself a longtime solidarity activist and 
political prisoner 
i deeply believe that in the poland which we are now building 
such a sacrifice will never be needed again mazowiecki said 
now walesa said poles must steel themselves for the difficult 
period ahead as the government submits a tough economic austerity 
program to parliament sunday 
urging poles to accept the painful measures he said the 
greatest polish tragedy would be to try to solve complicated 
economic problems of the country in the streets 
let our children enjoy what we will build for them and not 
have to sacrifice their lives to mend what their parents spoiled 
he said 
today to the fallen shipyard workers we must erect a different 
monument let it be a just democratic and prosperous poland 
scores of shipyard and port workers were killed in 1970 during 
riots and strikes that erupted in gdansk gdynia and szczecin when 
the communist leadership of wladyslaw gomulka announced sharp food 
price increases just before christmas 
walesa then a young shipyard worker participated in the 
strikes and later became active in illegal efforts to memorialize 
the victims whose exact number has never been known 
after the rise of solidarity in 1980 one of the unions first 
acts was to dedicate the monument of three steel crosses to the 
slain workers at the shipyard gate on dec 16 of that year the 
10th anniversary of the outbreak of the riots 
walesa recalled saturday that at that dedication he did not 
imagine that just a year later nine silesian coal miners would be 
gunned down in katowice in a second december the martiallaw 
crackdown authorities ordered to crush solidarity 
