mandatory water restrictions 
havent started yet in droughtparched south florida but 
complaints have 
environmentalists charge sensitive wildlife in the drying 
everglades are being shortchanged and golf course operators worry 
that the winter tourist trade may wither along with their greens 
the south florida water management district adopted mandatory 
limits thursday on lawn watering and home car washing for 4 million 
people from key west through miami and fort lauderdale to palm 
beach county to combat the worst drought in 27 years 
some parts of the southeast coast are 33 inches below normal 
rainfall levels for the last 14 months heading into the dry season 
which runs through may 
the restrictions take effect monday and the grumbling has 
already started 
in times of water shortage wildlife interests suffer first 
and benefit last said paul parks of the florida wildlife 
federation we dont have a true water allocation system that 
actually shares adversity 
district policy says all water users must share the pain of 
water cutbacks 
nevertheless rosa durando of the audubon society of the 
everglades is upset that half of the 61 billion gallons of water 
diverted in november from the loxahatchee national wildlife refuge 
was shifted to sugar cane and vegetable farms the other half went 
into storage at lake okeechobee a primary drinking water source 
what crop thats grown in america other than sugar has a 
guarantee first and above anybody else against the vagaries of 
nature she said 
but ed barber of the florida sugar cane league said the 
diversion was a drop in the bucket that amounted to only a 
threeweek water supply at rationed levels 
everybodys going to get hit hard barber said frankly 
it is such a serious situation that were not placing blame on 
anyone 
meanwhile golf course operators are concerned about the 
implications of the cutbacks for their business a 5 billion a 
year business in the sunshine state 
a complex set of rules allows the watering of greens only at 
