a recently unearthed state department memo 
shows that former secretary of state george p shultz approved a 
1985 white house plan to expedite us assistance to honduras to 
encourage the hondurans to remain firm in their support of the 
nicaraguan contras 
congressional officials regard the document as further proof of 
a quid pro quo to expedite us aid to honduras in return for 
that countrys support for the contra rebels fighting nicaraguas 
leftist government a source said saturday at the time congress 
had banned military aid to the contras 
they believe it also shows that shultz knew about the 
arrangement contrary to his statements to congress the source 
said 
the key document a feb 7 1985 memo from former assistant 
secretary langhorne a motley to shultz was turned up in a new 
search related to the irancontra trial of former national security 
adviser john poindexter 
the classified document now declassified was sent to several 
congressional committees on dec 5 with an explanation that it had 
not been turned up in earlier searches because of a computer 
matching problem 
the committee also received memos dated feb 13 and feb 19 
offering progress reports on the plan one of those describes 
efforts to move forward with a 35 million installment of us 
foreign aid to honduras and fulfillment of the quid pro quo 
deal 
its very telling said one congressional source 
as initially reported by the washington post motleys memo 
describes a white house meeting in which officials agreed on a 
course of action to bolster honduran support of the nicaraguan 
rebels 
it was agreed said the document initialled by shultz as 
his sign of approval that some combination of efforts was needed 
to encourage the hondurans to remain firm 
it went on to spell out a plan for expedited economic and 
military aid to honduras including an envisioned letter from 
thenpresident reagan to roberto suazo cordova then president of 
honduras although the presidents letter would not be explicitly 
linked to the specific reassuring actions listed above our 
intentions and expectations would be made clear in an oral demarche 
presentation the motley memo said 
the plan ultimately approved by reagan also contemplated other 
meetings with suazo including one by thenvice president bush 
questions were raised during the irancontra trial of 
poindexters deputy oliver north as to whether bush in his march 
16 1985 meeting with suazo had delivered a secret arrangement for 
helping the contras through honduras 
bush told reporters on may 4 there was no such discussion 
honduras there was no quid pro quo everybody that attended 
the meeting says there was no quid pro quo the word of the 
president of the united states george bush is there was no quid 
pro quo 
shultz who was said by his office to be traveling and 
unavailable for comment has repeatedly told congress that he was 
opposed to conditioning us aid to honduras on its support of the 
contras and that his view prevailed 
motley told the post that the document actually supports prior 
contentions there was no such deal he acknowledged that us 
officials informed honduras about their concerns for the contras 
and in turn entertained honduran requests for expedited assistance 
but that he said did not constitute a quid pro quo because no 
american ever offered to trade a for b 
rep david r obey dwis chairman of the house appropriations 
subcommittee on foreign operations said the discovery of the 
motley memo illustrates the correctness of our continuing to 
pursue the irancontra affair it also illustrates why there is 
such continuing suspicion on the part of congress of how much of 
the truth we are getting 
poindexter who headed the feb 7 1985 meeting described by 
motley faces five felony charges for his role in the irancontra 
affair 
