<TEXT>
vietnamese refugees demonstrated saturday to 
protest the forced repatriation of their compatriots in hong kong 
and released 51 black balloons one for each person returned to 
hanoi 
about 150 people attended the rally the first of a series 
planned around the country by the vietnam refugee national council 
to protest britains decision to repatriate boat people last week 
britain argues that most of the vietnamese confined to squalid 
camps in hong kong were fleeing poverty when they left their 
homeland not persecution and therefore dont qualify for refugee 
status 
the deportations tuesday were the first of thousands expected in 
coming years about 12000 boat people in hong kong have qualified 
as refugees under united nations criteria and will be resettled 
but about 44000 others face repatriation 
the protesters and their supporters gathered in trafalgar square 
in the rain and sang the old vietnamese national anthem in use 
before the communists came to power in 1975 then they stood 
silently in memory of those who died fighting communist oppression 
and listened to a series of speakers 
repatriation is evil guitarist steve hackett of the rock 
group genesis told the crowd we urge the hong kong government to 
dismantle the fences and the compounds 
hackett is the organizer of a group of musicians called rock 
against repatriation which is making a special recording of the 
song sailing once a hit for rod stewart with proceeds going 
to improve camp conditions it is expected to be released jan 20 
the rev michael meadows who worked in the former south 
vietnamese capital of saigon told the protesters our government 
ought not to be too gullible in accepting assurances from the 
government of hanoi that these people will be properly treated on 
their return 
vietnam has a very poor record on human rights and we ought to 
think once or twice before accepting their assurances he said 
foreign secretary douglas hurd has said the british embassy in 
hanoi will monitor the treatment of those returning but opposition 
lawmakers said it would be impossible to do that with such a small 
staff 
vietnam has told britain it rejects any forced repatriation of 
boat people from hong kong and reserves the right to send them back 
to the british colony 
a vietnam news agency report monitored in bangkok saturday said 
a foreign ministry official on friday delivered a note on vietnams 
position to the british ambassador to hanoi emrys davies 
the agency said the note affirmed the policy of rejecting forced 
repatriation and and only accepting those who volunteer to return 
or who are not opposed to the repatriation 
a british foreign office spokesman said the vietnamese message 
did not represent a change in that countrys position and that 
there would be no change in british policy 
britain has been criticized especially in the united states 
for forcibly returning the refugees 
the house of commons will debate the deportations on tuesday 
the government has halted further repatriations until after 
christmas 
