<TEXT>
lee iacocca t boone pickens and robert campeau 
swaggered triumphantly through most the 1980s admired feared and 
envied for their business brilliance wealth and foresight 
but the baying bloodhounds of economic reality treed them this 
past week the latest examples of how a weakening economy borrowed 
money and strategic blunders have humbled some of the decades 
biggest financial celebrities 
iacocca the chrysler corp chairman who led the rescue of the 
no 3 automaker from failure in the late 1970s once was hailed as 
a national hero when he announced early repayment of government 
bailout loans in 1983 iacocca boasted we at chrysler borrow 
money the old fashioned way we pay it back 
but over the past several months chryslers financial 
performance has deteriorated sharply and forced the company into a 
severe retreat because of brutal competition and the declining 
demand for cars and trucks 
in july iacocca proclaimed a 1 billion costcutting program 
earlier this month he scrapped a diversification plan and 
announced plans to sell chryslers aerospace division to raise more 
money 
this past week chrysler announced big rebates to unload 
backlogs of cars and trucks but the most telling element of the 
strategy was its firstever rebates on minivans formerly one of 
the automakers most popular sellers capturing more than half the 
market now chrysler is fighting to hold even part of that in the 
face of rivals from ford motor co general motors corp and japan 
for pickens the takeover strategist who epitomized the 1980s 
corporate raider and often denounced target companies for 
mismanagement this past week offered what critics called a 
sobering lesson in how he mismanaged his own 
the mesa limited partnership pickens energy company 
eliminated cash distributions to its unit holders the equivalent 
of eliminating dividend payments to shareholders and announced 
asset sales to repay debts including an interest in its prized 
kansas natural gas field 
pickens said the steps were necessary because of an unexpectedly 
prolonged depression in the price of natural gas mesas most 
important source of earnings 
but it was considered an ironic retreat by an outspoken defender 
of shareholder rights pickens had been borrowing money and using 
profits from his own takeover forays to maintain the cash 
distributions to mesas constituents 
for campeau whose multibillion dollar string of debtfinanced 
takeovers gave him an enormous retailing empire the past week was 
a christmas reminder that theres no santa claus when creditors 
call 
the canadian investor forced to put his crown jewel 
bloomingdales stores up for sale in september because of trouble 
repaying debts disclosed that he was having even more trouble 
despite an emergency cash infusion from lenders 
the announcement seemed to suggest that even the crucial holiday 
selling season might not tide over many of campeaus cashstarved 
stores it jolted the already weak market for highyield junk bond 
debt that campeau and other big takeover investors have sold to 
finance their expansions in the 1980s 
it also raised the prospect that campeau might put part of his 
holdings under bankruptcy court protection from creditors and by 
the end of the week that possibility seemed more like a 
selffulfilling prophecy 
heller financial inc one of the nations biggest lenders in 
the retailing industry said it no longer would extend credit to 
suppliers of campeaus stores 
in other business and economic news this past week 
chrysler wasnt the only automaker facing problems all of the 
big three and several foreign competitors announced slow us sales 
and some suggested they would have to idle thousands of workers 
unless orders picked up the sluggishness spread to europe where 
swedens troubled saabscania ab said it would sell a half interest 
in its passenger carbuilding business to gm 
most government statistics suggested much slower economic 
growth giving the federal reserve more flexibility to lower 
interest rates industrial production barely grew in november 
wholesale prices fell business inventories expanded in october and 
sales fell but the trade deficit for october surged nearly 20 
percent from a month earlier suggesting that americas appetite 
for foreign goods remains unabated 
prosecutors notched another courtroom victory in the ivan 
boesky insider trading scandal showing that juries increasingly 
are willing to convict wealthy defendants in complex securities 
fraud cases gaf corp and its vice chairman james t sherwin were 
found guilty of stock manipulation 
